00:11:57.550 --> 00:11:58.710
for us to discuss.

00:11:58.710 --> 00:12:01.020
And therefore we are
going to have an entire

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:04.930
separate episode related
to bipolar depression.

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:06.880
Today, we're going to talk
about major depression,

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:09.440
also sometimes called unipolar depression,

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:11.660
just because it doesn't
have the highs and lows.

00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:14.003
It's more characterized by the lows.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.440
We're going to talk about the biology,

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:19.780
the psychology, and
the various treatments,

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:22.660
behavioral, drug,
supplementation, diet, exercise,

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:23.510
all of that.

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:25.390
Before we go forward into the material,

00:12:25.390 --> 00:12:27.830
I just want to emphasize
that any discussion

00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:29.890
about mood disorders carries with it

00:12:29.890 --> 00:12:32.100
a particular sensitivity,

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:35.423
and that sensitivity is one
related to self-diagnosis.

00:12:36.590 --> 00:12:39.590
Today's episode, and indeed
in the future episodes

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:41.480
for this month on mood disorders,

00:12:41.480 --> 00:12:44.420
you're going to hear various
symptomologies that are used

00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:47.223
to diagnose and characterize
these disorders.

00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:51.610
If you recognize some of these
symptomologies in yourself

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:53.380
or in others that you know,

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:55.260
that's an important thing to take note of.

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:59.330
However, accurate diagnosis
really should be done

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:01.370
by a qualified healthcare professional.

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:04.430
So at once I'm saying, keep
your eyes and your ears up

00:13:04.430 --> 00:13:06.380
for things that sound familiar to you

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:07.500
that might be of concern.

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:08.340
And at the same time,

00:13:08.340 --> 00:13:11.630
I'm saying don't necessarily
leap to conclusions.

00:13:11.630 --> 00:13:14.140
Take those flags of
concern if they're there

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:16.510
and bring them to a qualified
healthcare professional,

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:20.010
and they'll be able to
properly diagnose you

00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.770
as having a particular mood
disorder or diagnose somebody

00:13:22.770 --> 00:13:25.060
as having a particular
mood disorder or not.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:26.940
And that's an essential step.

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:28.330
I don't say this to protect us,

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:30.660
I said this really to protect you.

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:34.700
Okay, let's have a fact-based
discussion about depression.

00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:38.330
And I promise you that where
we don't know certain things

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:40.730
about depression, I will
be clear to tell you.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:42.590
In fact, we are going to
talk about some treatments

00:13:42.590 --> 00:13:45.090
for depression that are
looking very promising,

00:13:45.090 --> 00:13:48.960
and that right now are actually
being used more and more.

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:52.350
And from my read of the
mechanistic literature,

00:13:52.350 --> 00:13:54.960
we're still a bit in the
dark as to how these work.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:56.560
That's actually a common
theme of medicine.

00:13:56.560 --> 00:13:59.570
Many times there are
treatments that seem promising

00:13:59.570 --> 00:14:01.650
or that look really terrific.

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:04.540
And there isn't a lot of
understanding about mechanism.

00:14:04.540 --> 00:14:07.420
However, any good discussion
about neuroscience

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:09.080
and in particular about mood disorders,

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:10.410
has to get into mechanisms.

00:14:10.410 --> 00:14:11.410
So we're going to do that.

00:14:11.410 --> 00:14:15.070
And in doing that, we're
going to frame the discussion

00:14:15.070 --> 00:14:18.220
for the tools of how to
keep depression at bay

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:19.470
and how to deal with it

00:14:19.470 --> 00:14:21.070
if you happen to find yourself depressed,

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:24.030
or if you know somebody
else who's depressed.

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:26.530
What is this thing we call depression?

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:28.480
Was I mentioned before, it has two forms,

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:31.380
bipolar depression, which
we're not talking about today,

00:14:31.380 --> 00:14:35.350
and major depression, also
called unipolar depression

00:14:35.350 --> 00:14:36.183
is the other.

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:41.720
Major depression impacts
5% of the population.

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:44.190
That is any enormous number.

00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:46.830
That means if you're in
a class of 100 people,

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:49.100
five of them are dealing
with major depression

00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:51.200
or have at some point.

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:52.670
Look around you in any environment

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:56.580
and you can be sure that a
good portion of the people

00:14:56.580 --> 00:14:59.910
that you're surrounded by
is impacted by depression,

00:14:59.910 --> 00:15:01.300
or will be at some point.

00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:03.160
So this is something we
really have to take seriously

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:04.623
and that we want to understand.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:09.510
It is the number four cause of disability.

00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:12.430
A lot of people miss work, miss school,

00:15:12.430 --> 00:15:16.320
and before then likely perform
poorly in work or school

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:18.780
due to major depression.

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:22.690
Now there's a very serious
challenge in having a discussion

00:15:22.690 --> 00:15:25.540
about depression and it relates
directly to the challenges

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:27.083
in diagnosing depression.

00:15:27.920 --> 00:15:30.890
Earlier, I did an episode
with Dr. Karl Deisseroth,

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:33.500
who is indeed a medical doctor and a PhD.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:34.333
He's a psychiatrist.

00:15:34.333 --> 00:15:35.740
And he made a very important point,

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:39.920
which is that the field of
psychiatry and psychology

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:41.370
are confronted with a challenge,

00:15:41.370 --> 00:15:43.470
which is they're trying to
understand what's going on

00:15:43.470 --> 00:15:47.340
within the stuff that's in our brains

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:49.490
that's deep to our skulls.

00:15:49.490 --> 00:15:51.670
We don't have access to
that without brain imaging

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:53.550
and electrodes and things like that.

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:56.700
Someone just comes into the
office and the dissection tool

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:59.550
for depression so to speak is language.

00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:03.330
In order to determine if
somebody has depression or not,

00:16:03.330 --> 00:16:05.700
we have to use language,
how they talk about things,

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:07.300
also how they carry their body.

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:09.670
Also some general patterns of health.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:11.880
So let's talk about depression

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:14.550
the way that clinicians
talk about depression,

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:16.610
because one of the issues is that

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:19.210
we use the word depression loosely.

00:16:19.210 --> 00:16:21.737
A lot of people say,
"Oh, I'm so depressed.

00:16:21.737 --> 00:16:24.187
"I didn't get this job
or I'm so depressed.

00:16:24.187 --> 00:16:25.877
"I just don't know, I
had a really rough week

00:16:25.877 --> 00:16:27.267
"or I'm exhausted.

00:16:27.267 --> 00:16:29.187
"I'm so depressed or I'm so depressed

00:16:29.187 --> 00:16:30.527
"I thought I was going to go on vacation

00:16:30.527 --> 00:16:32.680
"and then they canceled the flight." Okay.

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:35.290
That is not clinical depression.

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:38.350
That's called being bummed
out, being sad or disappointed.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:39.810
Now that person might be depressed,

00:16:39.810 --> 00:16:41.070
but clinical depression

00:16:41.070 --> 00:16:43.930
actually has some very specific criteria.

00:16:43.930 --> 00:16:48.460
And those criteria are
mainly characterized

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:51.200
by the presence of certain things

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:54.620
and the absence of a
few particular things.

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:57.560
So let's talk about the
things that are present

00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:00.520
in somebody that has major depression.

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:03.930
First of all, there tends
to be a lot of grief.

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:05.170
There tends to be a lot of sadness.

00:17:05.170 --> 00:17:06.610
That's no surprise.

00:17:06.610 --> 00:17:10.180
The threshold to cry is often
a signature of depression.

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:12.200
Now that doesn't mean
that if you cry easily,

00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:13.040
that you're depressed.

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:15.150
Some people cry more easily than others,

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:17.610
but if you're somebody who
typically didn't cry easily

00:17:17.610 --> 00:17:20.290
and suddenly you find
yourself crying very easily,

00:17:20.290 --> 00:17:22.207
that could be a sign of depression.

00:17:22.207 --> 00:17:23.823
And I want to emphasize, could.

00:17:24.820 --> 00:17:27.430
There's also this thing
that we call anhedonia,

00:17:27.430 --> 00:17:30.460
a general lack of ability to enjoy things,

00:17:30.460 --> 00:17:33.120
things that typically or
previously we enjoyed.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.040
Things like food, things like
sex, things like exercise,

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.070
things like social gatherings,

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:41.190
a kind of lack of enjoyment
from those things.

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:44.360
Sometimes that lack of enjoyment is sad,

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:47.850
and sometimes it's just flat,
it's just kind of neutral.

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:49.980
It doesn't feel good
because nothing there.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:51.520
It's like bland food.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:55.490
It's like these experiences are analogous

00:17:55.490 --> 00:17:58.540
to biting into your
favorite article of food

00:17:58.540 --> 00:18:01.010
and it just not tasting very good.

00:18:01.010 --> 00:18:02.750
It just doesn't taste
like anything at all.

00:18:02.750 --> 00:18:06.010
And that's a common symptom
of major depression.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:08.230
The other one is guilt.

00:18:08.230 --> 00:18:11.160
Oftentimes people with
depression will feel very guilty

00:18:11.160 --> 00:18:12.830
about things they have done in the past,

00:18:12.830 --> 00:18:16.100
or they'll just generally
feel badly about themselves.

00:18:16.100 --> 00:18:18.600
And we're going to talk
about this because it relates

00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:20.340
to some of the more serious symptomology

00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:21.690
seen in depression sometimes,

00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:25.140
things like self harm,
mutilation, or even suicide.

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:28.640
But for the time being, we
want to frame up anhedonia,

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:31.860
this lack of ability to
achieve or experience pleasure,

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:34.720
or kind of a flat affect as it's called.

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:37.550
Sometimes even delusional thinking,

00:18:37.550 --> 00:18:39.150
negative delusional thinking,

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:43.120
and in particular anti-self confabulation.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:44.730
What is anti-self confabulation?

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:48.180
Well, first of all, confabulation
is an incredible aspect

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:50.250
of our mind and our nervous system.

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:53.520
You sometimes see other
forms of confabulation

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.460
in people who have memory deficits

00:18:55.460 --> 00:18:57.270
either because they have brain damage

00:18:57.270 --> 00:19:00.240
or they have age-related dementia.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:02.170
A good example of this would be someone

00:19:02.170 --> 00:19:05.960
with age related dementia
sometimes will find themselves

00:19:05.960 --> 00:19:09.660
in a location in the house and
not know how they got there.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.350
And if you ask them, "Oh,
what are you doing here?"

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:14.247
They will create these elaborate stories.

00:19:14.247 --> 00:19:16.827
"Oh, I was thinking about
going to the shopping today,

00:19:16.827 --> 00:19:19.017
"and I was going to take the bus,

00:19:19.017 --> 00:19:19.850
"and then I was going to do this."

00:19:19.850 --> 00:19:23.020
They create these elaborate
stories, they confabulate.

00:19:23.020 --> 00:19:25.110
And yet that person hasn't
left the house in weeks

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:26.780
and that person doesn't
have a driver's license.

00:19:26.780 --> 00:19:28.670
And so they're really
just creating this stuff.

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:30.780
They're not lying to get out of anything,

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:31.710
they're confabulating.

00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:34.400
It's as if a brain circuit
that writes stories,

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.713
just starts generating content.

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:38.780
In major depression,

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:42.640
there's often a state of
delusional anti-self confabulation,

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:45.940
where the confabulation are not directly

00:19:45.940 --> 00:19:48.190
or completely linked to reality,

00:19:48.190 --> 00:19:50.870
but they are ones that make the self,

00:19:50.870 --> 00:19:52.550
the person describing them,

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:56.950
seem sick or in some way not well.

00:19:56.950 --> 00:19:58.250
A good example would be somebody

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:00.820
who experiences a physical injury perhaps.

00:20:00.820 --> 00:20:02.930
Maybe they break their
ankle, maybe it's an athlete,

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:06.300
and they also happen to become depressed.

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:07.987
And you'll talk to them and
say, "How are things going?

00:20:07.987 --> 00:20:09.233
"How's your rehab though?"

00:20:09.233 --> 00:20:11.097
And they go, "Oh, it's
okay. And I don't know.

00:20:11.097 --> 00:20:13.497
"I feel like I'm getting
weaker and weaker by the day.

00:20:13.497 --> 00:20:14.607
"I'm just not performing well."

00:20:14.607 --> 00:20:16.100
And then you'll talk to the person

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:17.750
that they're working with,

00:20:17.750 --> 00:20:21.150
their kinesiologist or whoever
the physical therapist is.

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:22.987
And they'll say, "No, they're
actually really improving.

00:20:22.987 --> 00:20:24.057
"And I tell them they're improving,

00:20:24.057 --> 00:20:26.757
"but somehow they're not
seeing that improvement,

00:20:26.757 --> 00:20:28.660
"they're not registering
that improvement."

00:20:28.660 --> 00:20:30.500
You notice that sometimes it's subtle

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:33.760
and sometimes it's severe, but
they'll start confabulating.

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:36.367
You'll say, "I actually heard
you're doing much better.

00:20:36.367 --> 00:20:39.337
"You're getting better,
you're taking multiple trips

00:20:39.337 --> 00:20:40.287
"around the building now

00:20:40.287 --> 00:20:42.130
"before you could barely get out of bed."

00:20:42.130 --> 00:20:43.177
And they'll say,

00:20:43.177 --> 00:20:45.537
"Yeah, well basically,
they changed some things

00:20:45.537 --> 00:20:48.717
"about the parking lot that
make it easier to move around.

00:20:48.717 --> 00:20:50.130
"So it's not really me."

00:20:50.130 --> 00:20:52.450
And these aren't people that
are just explaining away

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:54.790
their accomplishments

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:57.030
'cause they're trying to brush off praise.

00:20:57.030 --> 00:20:59.420
They are viewing themselves

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:02.130
and they're confabulating
according to a view

00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:04.800
that is very self-deprecating

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:07.540
to the point where it doesn't
match up with reality.

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:08.950
It's not what other people see

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:11.530
and it's actually not
matched up with reality.

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:13.810
And that's a symptom of depression

00:21:13.810 --> 00:21:16.110
that I think we don't often think about

00:21:16.110 --> 00:21:18.060
or conceptualize enough.

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:19.477
So it's not just telling people,

00:21:19.477 --> 00:21:22.800
"oh yeah, it's not as good as
it seems. Everything's bad."

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:24.230
These people really believe that

00:21:24.230 --> 00:21:26.340
and it becomes disconnected from reality.

00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:28.410
So it's if they're sort
of sinking into a pit

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:31.010
and they're losing touch with
the realities of the world,

00:21:31.010 --> 00:21:33.010
including data about themselves,

00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:35.410
their ability to move and get around it,

00:21:35.410 --> 00:21:37.960
for example, in that particular instance

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:41.000
that I used as an example,
but there are others as well.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.400
The other common symptomology
of major depression

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:48.750
is what they call
vegetative symptoms, okay?

00:21:48.750 --> 00:21:52.300
So vegetative symptoms
are symptoms that occur

00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:55.100
without any thinking, without any doing,

00:21:55.100 --> 00:21:56.490
or without any confabulation.

00:21:56.490 --> 00:21:59.130
These are things that are
related to our core physiology.

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:00.490
The word vegetative,

00:22:00.490 --> 00:22:02.120
you might know it sounds like vegetable.

00:22:02.120 --> 00:22:04.570
It actually relates to
a system in the body

00:22:04.570 --> 00:22:06.200
that nowadays is more commonly called

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.530
the autonomic nervous system.

00:22:08.530 --> 00:22:10.407
The vegetative nervous system

00:22:10.407 --> 00:22:12.360
and the autonomic nervous system,

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:15.060
historically were considered
sort of one in the same.

00:22:15.060 --> 00:22:17.860
And it relates to things
like the stress response

00:22:17.860 --> 00:22:19.760
or to our ability to sleep.

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:21.330
So vegetative symptoms

00:22:21.330 --> 00:22:24.430
be things like constantly being exhausted.

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:26.770
The person just feels exhausted.

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:28.420
It's not because they exercise too much,

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:31.670
it's not necessarily because
of a life event, it could be,

00:22:31.670 --> 00:22:33.460
but they're just worn out.

00:22:33.460 --> 00:22:36.130
They don't have the energy they once had.

00:22:36.130 --> 00:22:39.430
So it's not in their heads, it's probably,

00:22:39.430 --> 00:22:41.630
and now I think we have good
data to support the fact

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:43.530
that there's something off,

00:22:43.530 --> 00:22:45.570
something is disrupted in the autonomic

00:22:45.570 --> 00:22:47.397
or so-called vegetative nervous system.

00:22:47.397 --> 00:22:49.450
And one of the most common symptoms

00:22:49.450 --> 00:22:51.270
of people with major depression,

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:55.540
one of the signs of major
depression is early waking

00:22:55.540 --> 00:22:57.610
and not being able to fall back asleep

00:22:57.610 --> 00:22:59.870
despite being exhausted.

00:22:59.870 --> 00:23:03.250
So waking up at 3:00 AM
or 4:00 AM or 5:00 AM

00:23:03.250 --> 00:23:06.260
just spontaneously and not
being able to go back to sleep.

00:23:06.260 --> 00:23:07.950
I want to emphasize that that could happen

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:12.000
for other reasons as well,
but it is a common symptom

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.570
or warning sign of major depression.

00:23:14.570 --> 00:23:16.993
So let's talk more about
sleep and depression.

00:23:17.930 --> 00:23:21.500
It's well-known that the
architecture of sleep

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:23.360
is disrupted in depression.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:24.700
What's the architecture of sleep?

00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:26.150
I've done entire episodes about this,

00:23:26.150 --> 00:23:28.380
but very briefly in two sentences,

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:31.180
although they're probably
be run on sentences,

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:32.540
early in the night,

00:23:32.540 --> 00:23:35.370
you tend to have slow wave
sleep more than REM sleep

00:23:35.370 --> 00:23:36.660
or Rapid Eye Movement sleep.

00:23:36.660 --> 00:23:37.540
As the night goes on,

00:23:37.540 --> 00:23:39.920
you tend to have more
Rapid Eye Movement sleep.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:42.450
That architecture of slow wave sleep

00:23:42.450 --> 00:23:44.880
preceding Rapid Eye Movement sleep

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:49.880
is radically disrupted
in major depression.

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:52.260
In addition, the pattern
of activity in the brain

00:23:52.260 --> 00:23:55.230
during particular phases
of sleep is disrupted.

00:23:55.230 --> 00:23:56.480
Now this is during sleep.

00:23:56.480 --> 00:23:57.790
So this can't be that people

00:23:57.790 --> 00:23:59.680
are creating this
situation for themselves.

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:03.160
These are real physiological
signs that something is off

00:24:03.160 --> 00:24:06.930
in this so-called autonomic
or vegetative nervous system.

00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:08.830
And then there are some
other things that relate

00:24:08.830 --> 00:24:10.830
to the autonomic nervous system,

00:24:10.830 --> 00:24:14.600
but that we normally think of
as more voluntary in nature.

00:24:14.600 --> 00:24:17.210
And these are things
like decreased appetite.

00:24:17.210 --> 00:24:21.210
So you can imagine that one
could have decreased appetite

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:22.720
because of the anhedonia,

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:24.700
the lack of pleasure from food, right?

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:25.800
If you don't enjoy food,

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:28.570
then you might be less
motivated to eat it.

00:24:28.570 --> 00:24:29.720
That makes sense.

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:31.520
As well because of these disruptions

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:33.290
in the autonomic nervous system,

00:24:33.290 --> 00:24:35.570
these vegetative symptoms,
as they're called,

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:37.790
you can imagine that someone
would have decreased appetite

00:24:37.790 --> 00:24:40.569
because some of the hormones
associated with appetite,

00:24:40.569 --> 00:24:43.900
hypocretin orexin and things
of that sort, ghrelin,

00:24:43.900 --> 00:24:45.520
that those will be disrupted.

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:47.710
And if those names of
hypocretin orexin and ghrelin

00:24:47.710 --> 00:24:49.860
don't make any sense to
you, don't worry about it.

00:24:49.860 --> 00:24:53.210
What those are just hormones
that impact when we eat,

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:57.170
when we feel hungry, and
when we crave food more,

00:24:57.170 --> 00:24:58.650
as well as when we feel full,

00:24:58.650 --> 00:25:00.480
we have enough so-called satiety.

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:01.730
If you want to learn more about those,

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:04.750
we did entire episodes
on eating and metabolism.

00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:07.970
So you can see that the
symptomology of major depression

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:09.830
impacts us at multiple levels.

00:25:09.830 --> 00:25:14.200
There's the conscious level of
how excited we are generally.

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:15.380
Well, that's reduced.

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:18.620
There's grief, there's
guilt, there's crying,

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:20.690
but then there's also
these vegetative things.

00:25:20.690 --> 00:25:21.900
There's disruptions in sleep,

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:23.880
which of course make
everything more challenging

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:24.713
when we're awake.

00:25:24.713 --> 00:25:27.060
We know that sleep is
so vital for resetting.

00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:29.140
You're waking up early, you
can't get back to sleep.

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:32.880
That's going to adjust your affect,

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:34.390
your emotions in negative ways.

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:35.570
We know this.

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:36.960
And appetite is off.

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:39.520
And there are hormones that get disrupted.

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:41.680
So cortisol levels are increased.

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:44.650
In particular, there's a
signature pattern of depression

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:48.090
whereby cortisol, the
stress hormone that normally

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:49.760
is released in a healthy way

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:51.940
only in the early part of the day

00:25:51.940 --> 00:25:54.770
is shifted to late in the day.

00:25:54.770 --> 00:25:57.550
In fact, a 9:00 PM peak in cortisol

00:25:57.550 --> 00:26:01.040
is one of the physiological signatures

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:02.860
of depressive like states.

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:06.490
It's not the only one, but
it is an important one.

00:26:06.490 --> 00:26:08.560
So there are a lot of things
going on in major depression.

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:10.040
And by now you're probably thinking,

00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:11.230
goodness, this is dreadful.

00:26:11.230 --> 00:26:12.550
Like there's all this terrible stuff.

00:26:12.550 --> 00:26:14.520
And indeed it is terrible.

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:17.460
It is a terrible thing to find oneself

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:20.700
in a mode where things
feel sad, you feel guilty,

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:22.090
you're exhausted.

00:26:22.090 --> 00:26:24.530
And oftentimes there's also an association

00:26:24.530 --> 00:26:26.660
with the anxiety system.

00:26:26.660 --> 00:26:28.420
So just because people are exhausted

00:26:28.420 --> 00:26:30.340
and lethargic and they don't enjoy things,

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:33.360
doesn't necessarily mean that
there's an absence of anxiety.

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:34.690
There can also be a lot of anxiety

00:26:34.690 --> 00:26:35.960
about what's going to happen to me.

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:38.160
Am I going to be able to
achieve my goals in life?

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:40.570
Will I ever get out of this state?

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:42.470
And so things really start to layer on.

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:44.620
And if this sounds depressing to you,

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:46.410
it is indeed depressing.

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:49.760
This is really the place that
many people find themselves.

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:51.560
And it's a pit that they just don't know

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:52.980
how to climb out of.

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:54.750
So let's just take a few minutes

00:26:54.750 --> 00:26:57.420
and talk about some of
the underlying biology

00:26:57.420 --> 00:27:01.320
that creates this cloud
or this constellation

00:27:01.320 --> 00:27:02.990
of symptomology.

00:27:02.990 --> 00:27:04.430
I think that's really important to do

00:27:04.430 --> 00:27:08.220
because if we want to understand
the various treatments,

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:10.710
how they work and why they
work and how to implement them,

00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:13.290
we have to understand some
of the underlying biology.

00:27:13.290 --> 00:27:14.300
So let's spend a few minutes

00:27:14.300 --> 00:27:16.790
talking about the biology of depression,

00:27:16.790 --> 00:27:18.520
what's known and what's not known.

00:27:18.520 --> 00:27:19.840
Because in doing that,

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:21.910
I think you'll get a much clearer picture

00:27:21.910 --> 00:27:25.060
about why certain tools
work to relieve depression

00:27:25.060 --> 00:27:26.733
and why others might not.

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:31.090
So one of the most
important early findings

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:35.230
in the search for a
biological basis of depression

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:38.000
was this finding that there are drugs

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.883
that relieve some of the
symptoms of depression.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.560
Those drugs generally fall
into three major categories,

00:27:45.560 --> 00:27:48.370
but the first set of
ones that were discovered

00:27:48.370 --> 00:27:51.830
were the so-called
tricyclic antidepressants,

00:27:51.830 --> 00:27:56.830
and the MAO inhibitors, the
monoamine oxidase inhibitors.

00:27:57.170 --> 00:27:59.080
You don't need to understand
that nomenclature,

00:27:59.080 --> 00:28:00.630
but I'm going to give you
a little bit of detail

00:28:00.630 --> 00:28:03.530
so that if you want to
understand it, you can.

00:28:03.530 --> 00:28:06.800
Most of this work took
place in the late 1950s

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:11.360
and in the 1960s, and
continued well until the 1980s

00:28:11.360 --> 00:28:13.920
when new classes of drugs were discovered.

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:17.790
And these tricyclic antidepressants
and the MAO inhibitors

00:28:18.790 --> 00:28:23.490
largely worked by increasing
levels of norepinephrine

00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:27.140
in the brain, as well as
in the body, in some cases.

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:28.480
And they were discovered

00:28:28.480 --> 00:28:30.350
through a kind of odd
set of circumstances.

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:31.860
We don't have time to
go into all the history,

00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:34.170
but suffice to say that
they were discovered

00:28:34.170 --> 00:28:36.800
because of the exploration for drugs

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.370
that alter blood pressure.

00:28:39.370 --> 00:28:41.960
Norepinephrine impacts blood pressure,

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:45.230
and drugs that lower blood pressure

00:28:45.230 --> 00:28:47.460
reduce levels of norepinephrine.

00:28:47.460 --> 00:28:51.320
And that in many cases, was
shown to lead to depression

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:53.370
or depressive like symptoms.

00:28:53.370 --> 00:28:55.750
And so these drugs, these tricyclic drugs,

00:28:55.750 --> 00:28:59.790
and the MAO inhibitors actually
increase norepinephrine.

00:28:59.790 --> 00:29:03.820
And frankly, they do quite a
good job of relieving some,

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:07.420
if not all of the symptoms
of major depression.

00:29:07.420 --> 00:29:10.210
However, they carry with
the many side effects.

00:29:10.210 --> 00:29:12.580
Some of those side
effects are side effects

00:29:12.580 --> 00:29:13.990
related to blood pressure itself,

00:29:13.990 --> 00:29:17.640
by increasing noradrenaline,
norepinephrine as it's called,

00:29:17.640 --> 00:29:18.740
you raise blood pressure.

00:29:18.740 --> 00:29:21.630
That can be dangerous,
that can be uncomfortable.

00:29:21.630 --> 00:29:25.030
But they also have a lot
of other side effects.

00:29:25.030 --> 00:29:26.710
The reason they have other side effects

00:29:26.710 --> 00:29:30.220
is because they impact systems
in the brain and in the body

00:29:30.220 --> 00:29:35.070
that impact things like
libido, appetite, digestion,

00:29:35.070 --> 00:29:35.903
and others.

00:29:35.903 --> 00:29:38.320
And we'll talk about each
of those in sequence.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:41.190
Okay, so the experience
that clinicians had

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:44.190
of observing some relief for depression

00:29:44.190 --> 00:29:48.190
with the tricyclic antidepressants
and with MAO inhibitors

00:29:48.190 --> 00:29:50.450
was terrific, but there
were all these side effects,

00:29:50.450 --> 00:29:52.500
side effects that people
really did not like,

00:29:52.500 --> 00:29:54.562
they didn't like these drugs at all.

00:29:54.562 --> 00:29:57.170
A lot of people get dry mouth,
I mentioned the low libido,

00:29:57.170 --> 00:30:00.050
they'd have sleep issues,
appetite issues, weight gain.

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:01.510
They made some people so uncomfortable

00:30:01.510 --> 00:30:03.020
that they preferred not to take them,

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:04.870
even though when they didn't take them,

00:30:04.870 --> 00:30:06.760
they had a worsening or a maintenance

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:08.210
of their depressive symptoms.

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:12.900
A decade or so later,
there was the discovery

00:30:12.900 --> 00:30:15.540
of the so-called pleasure
pathways in the brain.

00:30:15.540 --> 00:30:18.430
These are pathways,
literally groups of neurons

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:20.560
that reside in different
locations in the brain

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:21.630
but connect to one another.

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:22.930
So it's a circuit.

00:30:22.930 --> 00:30:27.930
And when you stimulate these
neurons with certain behaviors

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:30.700
or with electrical
stimulation in an experiment,

00:30:30.700 --> 00:30:31.533
believe it or not,

00:30:31.533 --> 00:30:33.660
that's been done in
both animals and humans,

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:36.720
animals and humans become
very, very motivated

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:39.700
to get more stimulation of these pathways.

00:30:39.700 --> 00:30:42.450
So this pleasure pathway or
these circuits for pleasure

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:45.363
are very what we call reinforcing.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:51.650
In fact, animals and humans will work hard

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:54.060
to get stimulation of these brain areas

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:58.640
even more than they will
work to obtain sex, drugs,

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:01.260
or even if they are addicted
to a particular drug

00:31:01.260 --> 00:31:02.900
and they are in a state of withdrawal,

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:05.170
the ultimate state of craving,

00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:07.880
if given a choice, a person or an animal

00:31:07.880 --> 00:31:11.930
will select to have stimulation
of this pleasure pathway

00:31:11.930 --> 00:31:14.110
instead of the drug itself.

00:31:14.110 --> 00:31:17.110
And that is a major and
significant finding.

00:31:17.110 --> 00:31:19.870
This pleasure pathway,
as it's sometimes called,

00:31:19.870 --> 00:31:22.110
involves areas like the nucleus accumbens

00:31:22.110 --> 00:31:23.980
and the ventral tegmental area.

00:31:23.980 --> 00:31:25.380
These are areas of the brain

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:28.550
that are rich with neurons
that make dopamine.

00:31:28.550 --> 00:31:30.940
And if you think to the
symptoms of depression,

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:32.800
of anhedonia, lack of pleasure,

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:35.380
a lack of ability to experience pleasure,

00:31:35.380 --> 00:31:39.470
well, that was a smoking gun
that there's something wrong

00:31:39.470 --> 00:31:42.330
with the dopamine pathway in depression.

00:31:42.330 --> 00:31:43.290
And indeed that's the case.

00:31:43.290 --> 00:31:44.670
So it's not just norepinephrine,

00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:47.010
it's also the dopamine or pleasure pathway

00:31:47.010 --> 00:31:48.690
is somehow disrupted.

00:31:48.690 --> 00:31:50.390
And then in the 1980s,

00:31:50.390 --> 00:31:53.020
there was the discovery
of the so-called SSRIs

00:31:53.020 --> 00:31:55.280
Most people are now
familiar with the SSRIs,

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:58.440
the Selective Serotonin
Re-Uptake Inhibitors.

00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:02.020
The SSRIs worked by distinct mechanisms

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:06.090
from the tricyclic antidepressants
and the MAO inhibitors.

00:32:06.090 --> 00:32:08.210
As their name suggests, SSRI,

00:32:08.210 --> 00:32:11.050
Selective Serotonin Re-Uptake Inhibitors

00:32:11.050 --> 00:32:16.050
prevent serotonin from being
wiped up from the synapse

00:32:16.450 --> 00:32:18.370
after two neurons talk to one another.

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:19.240
What do I mean by that?

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:21.960
Well, here's some very
basic Neurobiology 101.

00:32:21.960 --> 00:32:23.610
If you don't know any neurobiology,

00:32:23.610 --> 00:32:26.510
you're going to know
some in about 15 seconds.

00:32:26.510 --> 00:32:28.580
Neurons communicate with one another

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:32.560
by spitting out chemicals into
the little gap between them.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:34.740
The little gap between
them is called the synapse

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:37.360
or by the Brits, the synapse.

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:40.900
Those chemicals bind to the
neuron on the opposite side

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:44.020
and cause changes in the
electrical activity of that neuron

00:32:44.020 --> 00:32:46.330
on the other side of the synapse.

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:49.070
Serotonin is one such neurotransmitter

00:32:49.070 --> 00:32:51.750
or more specifically,
it's a neuromodulator,

00:32:51.750 --> 00:32:54.550
can change the activity
of large groups of neurons

00:32:54.550 --> 00:32:55.940
in very meaningful ways.

00:32:55.940 --> 00:32:58.460
Selective serotonin re-uptake inhibitor

00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:02.090
means when a person takes this drug,

00:33:02.090 --> 00:33:05.200
some of those drugs include
things like Prozac or Zoloft,

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:07.340
the more typical names
or more generic names

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:09.140
are things like fluoxetine,

00:33:09.140 --> 00:33:12.700
when people take those,
more serotonin hangs out

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:15.130
in the synapse and is able to be taken up

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:17.600
by the neuron on the opposite side

00:33:17.600 --> 00:33:22.360
because of this selective
re-uptake inhibition.

00:33:22.360 --> 00:33:26.740
It prevents the clearance of
serotonin from the synapse

00:33:26.740 --> 00:33:29.560
and thereby more serotonin
can have an effect.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:33.280
So SSRIs don't increase the
total amount of serotonin

00:33:33.280 --> 00:33:34.220
in the brain.

00:33:34.220 --> 00:33:37.960
They change how effective the serotonin

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:40.060
that's already in the brain is

00:33:40.060 --> 00:33:43.900
at changing the activity of neurons, okay?

00:33:43.900 --> 00:33:45.810
So they don't increase serotonin,

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:49.610
they increase the efficacy
or the function of serotonin

00:33:49.610 --> 00:33:51.590
in the way that I just described.

00:33:51.590 --> 00:33:53.040
So that was more than 15 seconds,

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:55.900
but now you understand how SSRIs work.

00:33:55.900 --> 00:33:58.220
And I wouldn't be talking about SSRIs

00:33:58.220 --> 00:34:00.143
if they didn't in fact work.

00:34:01.290 --> 00:34:03.850
Yes, there are many problems with SSRIs.

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:06.960
They do carry certain side
effects in many individuals.

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:11.270
Also, about a third of
people that take SSRIs

00:34:11.270 --> 00:34:13.070
don't derive any benefit,

00:34:13.070 --> 00:34:15.350
it doesn't relieve their
symptoms of depression.

00:34:15.350 --> 00:34:17.110
However, for the other two thirds,

00:34:17.110 --> 00:34:18.890
there's often a relief of some,

00:34:18.890 --> 00:34:21.520
if not all of the symptoms
of major depression.

00:34:21.520 --> 00:34:25.540
The problem is the side effects
that accompany those SSRIs.

00:34:25.540 --> 00:34:28.780
And so these days SSRIs
are a complicated topic.

00:34:28.780 --> 00:34:30.820
It's sort of what I would
call a barbed wire topic

00:34:30.820 --> 00:34:33.910
because we often hear about
all the problems with them,

00:34:33.910 --> 00:34:36.330
but these drugs also have
saved a lot of lives.

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:39.320
They've also improved a lot of lives.

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:42.690
The issue is that they tend
to have varying effects

00:34:42.690 --> 00:34:43.620
on different individuals,

00:34:43.620 --> 00:34:45.860
and sometimes varying effects over time.

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:48.360
So they'll work for awhile then
they won't work for a while.

00:34:48.360 --> 00:34:51.387
There are also a lot of
mysteries about the SSRIs,

00:34:51.387 --> 00:34:53.750
and those mysteries bother people.

00:34:53.750 --> 00:34:55.130
What mysteries am I referring to?

00:34:55.130 --> 00:34:59.360
Well, SSRIs increase
the amount of serotonin

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:02.120
or more specifically,
they increase the efficacy

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:05.900
of serotonin at the synapse,
that happens immediately,

00:35:05.900 --> 00:35:09.010
or very soon after people
start taking SSRIs.

00:35:09.010 --> 00:35:11.750
But people generally don't
start experiencing any relief

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:13.330
from their symptoms of depression

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:16.070
if they're going to
experience them at all,

00:35:16.070 --> 00:35:19.030
until about two weeks after
they start taking these drugs.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:21.420
So there's something going
on there that's not clear.

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:26.220
One idea is that the SSRIs
actually can improve symptoms

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:30.370
of depression or even remove
symptoms of depression

00:35:30.370 --> 00:35:32.870
through so-called neuro-plasticity

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:35.930
by changing the way that
neural circuits function.

00:35:35.930 --> 00:35:37.840
And there are many on this,

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:40.240
but the main categories
of studies on SSRIs

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:43.050
that relate to neuroplasticity
fall into two camps.

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:46.430
One is that the ways in which SSRIs might,

00:35:46.430 --> 00:35:48.610
and I want to emphasize,
might be able to trigger

00:35:48.610 --> 00:35:50.750
the production of more
neurons in the brain,

00:35:50.750 --> 00:35:53.240
in particular areas of the hippocampus

00:35:53.240 --> 00:35:57.520
called the dentate gyrus and
others, that impact memory.

00:35:57.520 --> 00:35:59.510
This is important. We're
going to come back to memory.

00:35:59.510 --> 00:36:02.560
The other is that the
SSRIs have been shown

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:06.860
in various scientific studies to reopen

00:36:06.860 --> 00:36:08.520
critical periods of plasticity.

00:36:08.520 --> 00:36:10.120
I'll just briefly describe
one of those studies.

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:14.430
There was a study done by
Lamberto Maffei's group in Pisa,

00:36:14.430 --> 00:36:16.840
that explored brain plasticity

00:36:16.840 --> 00:36:19.000
that's known to be
present in young animals

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.470
and disappear in older animals.

00:36:21.470 --> 00:36:24.550
And this is also true in
humans that younger humans

00:36:24.550 --> 00:36:26.580
have a far more plastic
brain that can change

00:36:26.580 --> 00:36:30.210
in many more ways more easily
than can the older brain.

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:33.400
And what they showed was
that fluoxetine, Prozac,

00:36:33.400 --> 00:36:37.630
given to adult animals can reopen

00:36:37.630 --> 00:36:39.920
this incredible period of plasticity,

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:42.670
can allow more plasticity to occur.

00:36:42.670 --> 00:36:43.503
That was interesting.

00:36:43.503 --> 00:36:44.870
I mean, it's purely through increases

00:36:44.870 --> 00:36:46.930
in serotonin transmission.

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:49.600
And there are other studies
showing that fluoxetine

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.040
can increase the number of new neurons

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:52.860
that are born into the adult brain,

00:36:52.860 --> 00:36:56.360
so called neurogenesis, the
production of new neurons.

00:36:56.360 --> 00:36:59.410
So it's very clear that there are at least

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:01.750
three major chemical systems in the brain;

00:37:01.750 --> 00:37:05.860
norepinephrine, dopamine,
and serotonin that relate to

00:37:05.860 --> 00:37:09.020
and can adjust the symptoms of depression.

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:12.160
And those actually can be
divided into separate categories.

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:15.970
So for instance, epinephrin
or norepinephrine

00:37:15.970 --> 00:37:19.370
is thought to relate to the
so-called psychomotor defects,

00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:21.410
sometimes called psychomotor retardation.

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:24.080
This is the lethargy,
this is the exhaustion,

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:26.790
this is the inability to get
out of bed in the morning.

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:30.350
Dopamine is thought to
relate to the anhedonia,

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:33.740
or I should say lack of
dopamine in depressive patients

00:37:33.740 --> 00:37:35.960
is thought to lead to the anhedonia.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:39.420
The lack of ability to
experience pleasure.

00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:44.420
And serotonin is thought to
relate to the grief, the guilt,

00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:48.070
some of the more cognitive
or more emotional aspects

00:37:48.070 --> 00:37:49.190
of depression.

00:37:49.190 --> 00:37:50.800
So we've got the norepinephrine system

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:52.970
related to activity and alertness,

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:55.460
the dopamine system
relating to motivation,

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:58.610
pleasure, and the ability to
seek and experience pleasure,

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:02.380
and then the serotonin system
that's related to grief.

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:04.870
And unfortunately, brains and organisms

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:07.930
don't work in a simple mathematical way

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:08.890
where you just say, oh, well,

00:38:08.890 --> 00:38:10.800
this person's experiencing a lot of grief,

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:14.490
but they don't have any
problems with lethargy.

00:38:14.490 --> 00:38:16.340
And so let's just boost
up their serotonin.

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:17.340
On paper it works,

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:19.630
but oftentimes it doesn't work clinically.

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:21.990
And another patient,
you might get somebody

00:38:21.990 --> 00:38:24.570
who can't experience pleasure,
but they're kind of anxious.

00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:26.157
They don't have any trouble sleeping,

00:38:26.157 --> 00:38:30.210
but they're just much more
anxious and frustrated

00:38:30.210 --> 00:38:31.170
than they normally are,

00:38:31.170 --> 00:38:33.280
and they meet the symptoms of depression.

00:38:33.280 --> 00:38:34.870
Well, you might think, oh, well,

00:38:34.870 --> 00:38:37.830
do you just give that person
some drugs increase dopamine

00:38:37.830 --> 00:38:38.800
and everything will be better?

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:40.780
And indeed, in some cases that's true.

00:38:40.780 --> 00:38:43.150
There are drugs like Wellbutrin,

00:38:43.150 --> 00:38:46.690
which function more specifically
on the dopamine system

00:38:46.690 --> 00:38:49.500
to increase dopamine and they
also increase norepinephrine.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:53.580
Many people get great relief
from things like Wellbutrin.

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:56.500
They don't really impact the
serotonin system so much.

00:38:56.500 --> 00:38:58.900
And therefore you don't get
a lot of the serotonergic

00:38:58.900 --> 00:39:00.960
or serotonin related side effects.

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:04.490
However, some people feel far
too anxious on those drugs,

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:07.450
some people get addicted
to those drugs in a way,

00:39:07.450 --> 00:39:09.850
because a lot of those
drugs that increase dopamine

00:39:09.850 --> 00:39:11.670
make you want more of those drugs.

00:39:11.670 --> 00:39:13.940
So you start to realize that
what makes sense on paper

00:39:13.940 --> 00:39:15.350
doesn't always make sense clinically.

00:39:15.350 --> 00:39:16.520
And this is why it's complicated.

00:39:16.520 --> 00:39:18.100
And a really good psychologist

00:39:18.100 --> 00:39:19.870
and a really good psychiatrist
will work with someone

00:39:19.870 --> 00:39:22.440
to try and pull and push
on these various systems

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:25.240
to find the combination
of drugs that may be

00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:27.123
or may not be correct for them.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.210
There's a fourth aspect of
the chemistry of depression

00:39:31.210 --> 00:39:32.550
that's really important to understand.

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:34.530
And that's pain.

00:39:34.530 --> 00:39:36.510
We've talked about pain
on this podcast before,

00:39:36.510 --> 00:39:38.430
but even if you didn't hear
the episode on pleasure

00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:41.120
and pain, just want to
emphasize that pain is something

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:43.260
that we experience in our
body, no surprise there,

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:45.140
an injury, a cut, et cetera,

00:39:45.140 --> 00:39:47.320
but that we also
experience emotional pain.

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:50.343
And those systems are linked
in very intricate ways.

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:55.150
There's actually some data
showing that pain relievers,

00:39:55.150 --> 00:39:56.920
Tylenol, Aspirin, these sorts of things,

00:39:56.920 --> 00:39:59.727
can help certain people
with emotional pain.

00:39:59.727 --> 00:40:01.400
Now I'm not recommending people run out

00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:03.230
and take those things for emotional pain.

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:04.190
But actually, if you think about it,

00:40:04.190 --> 00:40:05.670
that shouldn't come as any surprise.

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:09.080
given the enormous number of
people that take painkillers,

00:40:09.080 --> 00:40:11.180
opioids and things like
them to try and relieve

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:12.270
their psychological pain.

00:40:12.270 --> 00:40:16.430
And as we know, those drugs
are very, very problematic

00:40:16.430 --> 00:40:18.130
for many individuals.

00:40:18.130 --> 00:40:19.370
They can help certain individuals,

00:40:19.370 --> 00:40:21.760
but they are very prone to abuse

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:24.060
and they can induce addiction very easily

00:40:24.060 --> 00:40:25.350
in a number of people.

00:40:25.350 --> 00:40:29.500
There's a substance that's
literally called substance P,

00:40:29.500 --> 00:40:33.350
the letter P, that's manufactured
by neurons in our brain

00:40:33.350 --> 00:40:35.410
and body, which underlies
our sensation of pain.

00:40:35.410 --> 00:40:38.820
And indeed substance P
inhibitors have been used

00:40:38.820 --> 00:40:41.410
to treat depression,
and in some cases works.

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:45.060
A lot of people with depression
are hypersensitive to pain,

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:46.910
and of course they could have
multiple things going on.

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:48.900
They could have chronic
pain or chronic injury

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:50.360
and major depression.

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:51.760
So you start to get the constellation

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:53.910
of the many things that could happen.

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:57.530
So that's all I want to say
today about the chemistry

00:40:57.530 --> 00:41:01.190
underlying depression or major depression.

00:41:01.190 --> 00:41:02.200
There's a lot more there,

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:04.790
but I think if you understand
the norepinephrine system

00:41:04.790 --> 00:41:08.610
and that it relates to some
of these things like lethargy,

00:41:08.610 --> 00:41:11.430
the psychomotor defects,
as they're called,

00:41:11.430 --> 00:41:14.010
dopamine and how it relates to motivation

00:41:14.010 --> 00:41:17.010
and lack of motivation and lack
of dopamine and depression,

00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:20.340
and serotonin and its
relationship to grief,

00:41:20.340 --> 00:41:23.520
and that low serotonin can
lead to extreme grief and shame

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:26.020
and higher serotonin levels
can sometimes restore

00:41:26.020 --> 00:41:27.930
a sense of wellbeing and safety

00:41:27.930 --> 00:41:29.710
and feeling good about oneself.

00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:32.710
If you understand that and you
understand that physical pain

00:41:32.710 --> 00:41:34.450
is somehow involved in certain cases,

00:41:34.450 --> 00:41:37.107
I think you will know
more about depression

00:41:37.107 --> 00:41:39.860
and its underlying chemistry
than most all people out there.

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:40.860
And if you'd like to learn more,

00:41:40.860 --> 00:41:44.200
I invite you to pursue
searching those terms

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:45.400
further on the internet.

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:47.120
And we'll certainly go
into them in more depth.

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:50.170
But that really sets the stage
for where we're headed next.

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:51.820
So next I'd like to talk about hormones

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:53.970
and how they relate to depression.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:55.770
And I'd also like to talk about stress

00:41:55.770 --> 00:41:57.440
and how it relates to depression,

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:59.500
as well as talk about some of the genetics

00:41:59.500 --> 00:42:02.780
or the predispositions to depression.

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:03.970
And for those of you that are thinking,

00:42:03.970 --> 00:42:04.890
hey, I want the tools.

00:42:04.890 --> 00:42:07.110
I want to know how to fix depression.

00:42:07.110 --> 00:42:09.770
I understand the desire for that.

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:11.800
I will just ask if you
hang in here with me

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:14.070
a little bit longer, not only
will you learn a lot more

00:42:14.070 --> 00:42:18.030
about how this complicated
mood disorder works,

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:20.280
some of the more
interesting things about it,

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:22.470
but it will also position
you to get a lot more

00:42:22.470 --> 00:42:24.530
out of the tools that we will describe.

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:26.450
You always have the option
to skip forward of course,

00:42:26.450 --> 00:42:28.330
but I think it's important to understand

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:29.960
some of the hormonal and stress-related

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:31.580
aspects of depression.

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:33.113
So let's talk about hormones.

00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:37.230
20% of people that have major depression

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:39.370
have low thyroid hormone.

00:42:39.370 --> 00:42:41.663
Thyroid hormone is related to metabolism.

00:42:41.663 --> 00:42:44.500
Oftentimes we think about
thyroid is only related

00:42:44.500 --> 00:42:47.290
to having a fast metabolism,

00:42:47.290 --> 00:42:50.370
but thyroid is related to
all forms of metabolism,

00:42:50.370 --> 00:42:52.840
including our ability to
synthesize new tissues

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:55.470
like protein and repair injuries.

00:42:55.470 --> 00:42:58.500
I did a whole episode on
thyroid and growth hormone.

00:42:58.500 --> 00:42:59.530
If you want to check that out,

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:02.360
all of that is archived
at hubermanlab.com.

00:43:02.360 --> 00:43:03.740
It's all timestamped, et cetera.

00:43:03.740 --> 00:43:06.370
You can find on YouTube, Apple,
Spotify, all those places.

00:43:06.370 --> 00:43:07.930
So if you're curious about thyroid hormone

00:43:07.930 --> 00:43:10.700
and growth hormone, and you want
to do the deep dive on those,

00:43:10.700 --> 00:43:13.040
and you want to learn
how to alter their levels

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:15.680
using various approaches, check that out.

00:43:15.680 --> 00:43:20.380
But 20% of people with major
depression are hypo thyroidal.

00:43:20.380 --> 00:43:22.290
They don't make enough thyroid.

00:43:22.290 --> 00:43:24.280
And that leads to low energy,

00:43:24.280 --> 00:43:27.350
low metabolism in the brain and body.

00:43:27.350 --> 00:43:30.100
And there's a condition
called Hashimoto's,

00:43:30.100 --> 00:43:33.560
which is essentially low thyroid output.

00:43:33.560 --> 00:43:35.340
And again, I don't want
to get into all the tools

00:43:35.340 --> 00:43:36.173
related to thyroid.

00:43:36.173 --> 00:43:40.010
Sometimes a psychiatrists will
prescribe thyroid medication

00:43:40.010 --> 00:43:42.530
to increase thyroid output
in people that are depressed

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:44.560
and that will work to
relieve the symptoms.

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:46.940
So there isn't necessarily
a direct problem

00:43:46.940 --> 00:43:49.060
with serotonin, dopamine,
and norepinephrine

00:43:49.060 --> 00:43:49.893
or substance abuse.

00:43:49.893 --> 00:43:51.670
Sometimes it's a thyroid problem.

00:43:51.670 --> 00:43:54.180
So there are certain
situations or conditions

00:43:54.180 --> 00:43:57.170
that can impact the thyroid hormone system

00:43:57.170 --> 00:43:59.700
and make people more
susceptible to depression

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:02.040
or make a pre-existing depression worse.

00:44:02.040 --> 00:44:04.400
And those are things like childbirth.

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:06.810
So it's well-known that
women who give birth

00:44:06.810 --> 00:44:09.460
can often undergo what's
called postpartum depression.

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:13.810
It actually comes from the word
post parturition depression.

00:44:13.810 --> 00:44:15.202
They give birth,

00:44:15.202 --> 00:44:17.980
what's happier, what's
more joyful than the birth

00:44:17.980 --> 00:44:19.370
of a new healthy child,

00:44:19.370 --> 00:44:20.940
and they will lapse into a depression.

00:44:20.940 --> 00:44:23.400
And that's thought to
be hormonally related,

00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:25.990
either directly to the thyroid system

00:44:25.990 --> 00:44:27.800
or perhaps to the cortisol system as well.

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:29.490
We'll talk about cortisol in a moment.

00:44:29.490 --> 00:44:31.990
As well, certain women
during certain phases

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:34.980
of their menstrual cycle
experience symptoms

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:37.800
that are very much like
clinical depression,

00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:39.790
and oftentimes are diagnosed

00:44:39.790 --> 00:44:42.140
with clinical depression appropriately.

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:43.750
And of course the menstrual
cycle is associated

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:45.080
with shifts in hormone levels.

00:44:45.080 --> 00:44:48.670
As well, menopausal and
post-menopausal women

00:44:48.670 --> 00:44:51.520
are more susceptible to major depression,

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:52.810
regardless of whether or not they've had

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:54.430
that major depression
earlier in their life.

00:44:54.430 --> 00:44:56.220
So these are things to
be on the lookout for

00:44:56.220 --> 00:44:59.210
and to definitely talk to a
doctor and get a blood panel

00:44:59.210 --> 00:45:01.750
that hopefully includes
measures of thyroid hormone

00:45:01.750 --> 00:45:02.710
and cortisol hormone.

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:03.840
Why cortisol hormone?

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:07.270
Well more stress is
correlated with more bouts

00:45:07.270 --> 00:45:09.840
of major depression across the lifespan.

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:10.720
How many bouts?

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:13.530
Well, it turns out that as you go

00:45:13.530 --> 00:45:15.340
from having one to two to three,

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:17.650
well, when you hit four to five bouts

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:20.750
of really intense,
stressful episodes in life,

00:45:20.750 --> 00:45:23.310
these tend to be long-term
stressful episodes,

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:26.340
your risk for major
depression goes way up.

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:28.880
So whether or not you have
a genetic predisposition

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:31.080
to depression or not,

00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:33.020
one of the best things you can do

00:45:33.020 --> 00:45:34.540
to try and avoid getting depressed

00:45:34.540 --> 00:45:37.520
is to learn to control your stress system,

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:39.910
to not go from short-term stress,

00:45:39.910 --> 00:45:41.190
which everybody experiences,

00:45:41.190 --> 00:45:43.280
we all have short-term stressors,

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:45.440
to medium term stress to long-term stress,

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:47.820
and to not have too many
bouts of long-term stress

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:50.210
because that probability
of getting depressed

00:45:50.210 --> 00:45:51.430
goes way, way up.

00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:54.400
And this is something I've
seen over and over again,

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:56.930
not just in my scientific
career, but just throughout life.

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:59.560
People in all sorts of
domains, young and old,

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:01.470
I've seen that people will go through

00:46:01.470 --> 00:46:05.510
a very intense relationship, a breakup,

00:46:05.510 --> 00:46:07.510
sometimes it's the staying
together that stressful,

00:46:07.510 --> 00:46:10.920
sometimes it's a graduate
school that can be stressful,

00:46:10.920 --> 00:46:12.900
sometimes it's some other event.

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.600
And then some months later
they become depressed.

00:46:15.600 --> 00:46:17.260
And that's because the stress system

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:19.290
is associated with the
release of cortisol.

00:46:19.290 --> 00:46:21.507
The cortisol system
can dramatically impact

00:46:21.507 --> 00:46:23.930
the way that these
different neuromodulators,

00:46:23.930 --> 00:46:26.270
dopamine, norepinephrine
and serotonin function.

00:46:26.270 --> 00:46:30.470
And so there's this kind of
latent or longer lasting impact

00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:34.000
on the systems that
impact mood and wellbeing.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.440
So learning how to control
your stress is really key.

00:46:36.440 --> 00:46:38.960
If you're not depressed or you're somebody

00:46:38.960 --> 00:46:42.050
that has not lapsed into
a depression recently,

00:46:42.050 --> 00:46:43.710
take control of your stress system.

00:46:43.710 --> 00:46:46.600
And we did an entire episode
on how to conquer stress,

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.920
and that involves dealing
with stress in the short term,

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:50.480
the medium term, and in the long-term.

00:46:50.480 --> 00:46:52.650
And there are a lot of
different ways to do that.

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:54.640
One of the more important reasons

00:46:54.640 --> 00:46:56.190
for learning how to counter stress

00:46:56.190 --> 00:46:59.030
in order to offset depression

00:46:59.030 --> 00:47:01.970
is that there is a genetic predisposition

00:47:01.970 --> 00:47:04.570
that certain people carry
to become depressed.

00:47:04.570 --> 00:47:06.180
There are these studies now

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:08.290
of many, many thousands of individuals,

00:47:08.290 --> 00:47:09.910
these were mainly done in New Zealand,

00:47:09.910 --> 00:47:12.190
but these studies have
now been done elsewhere,

00:47:12.190 --> 00:47:15.510
looking at many tens of
thousands of individuals

00:47:15.510 --> 00:47:18.730
who carry particular copies of genes,

00:47:18.730 --> 00:47:20.600
what they call polymorphisms,

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:22.840
in particular of a gene called 5HTTLPR,

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:27.370
which is a serotonin transporter.

00:47:27.370 --> 00:47:29.910
So this is a gene that
controls or regulates

00:47:29.910 --> 00:47:32.670
how much serotonin is
available in the brain.

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:36.120
If you have this gene, this polymorphism,

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.490
it doesn't necessarily mean
that you will be depressed,

00:47:38.490 --> 00:47:43.340
but it greatly shifts your
susceptibility to depression

00:47:43.340 --> 00:47:45.230
under conditions of stress.

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:47.027
So I realize some people
are listening to this

00:47:47.027 --> 00:47:48.700
and some people are
watching it on YouTube.

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:49.890
So I'm going to describe this in a way

00:47:49.890 --> 00:47:52.010
that doesn't require
looking at any graphs.

00:47:52.010 --> 00:47:56.770
What I want you to imagine
is a very, shallow hill,

00:47:56.770 --> 00:47:58.140
like a very mellow hill.

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:02.720
It's just a ramp set at
about 10 or 15 degrees, okay.

00:48:02.720 --> 00:48:04.680
What we're plotting there in your mind

00:48:04.680 --> 00:48:09.680
is that with each about of serious stress,

00:48:09.950 --> 00:48:11.570
so that could be trying to finish a degree

00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:15.020
or a relationship breakup, or
a family member that's sick,

00:48:15.020 --> 00:48:16.770
or the loss of a loved one or a pet,

00:48:16.770 --> 00:48:19.810
with each about of stress, the probability

00:48:19.810 --> 00:48:23.100
that you will experience a
major depression goes up.

00:48:23.100 --> 00:48:28.100
However, if you carry this
gene, this HTTLPR gene,

00:48:29.870 --> 00:48:33.410
the steepness of that
curve goes way, way up

00:48:33.410 --> 00:48:35.080
where it's actually more like a line

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:39.520
such that you need far
fewer bouts of stress

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:42.420
in order to lapse into a
major depression, okay?

00:48:42.420 --> 00:48:46.050
So if the typical person who
doesn't carry this polymorphism

00:48:46.050 --> 00:48:48.870
has to experience two or
three or four or five bouts

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:51.970
of stress before they
lapse into a depression,

00:48:51.970 --> 00:48:55.480
somebody with this gene is
susceptible to getting depression

00:48:55.480 --> 00:48:59.240
after just one about or two
bouts of intense stress, okay?

00:48:59.240 --> 00:49:01.200
So that's how these genes work.

00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:05.840
They don't preordain or
determine you to be depressed.

00:49:05.840 --> 00:49:07.470
They raise a susceptibility.

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:09.070
And many genes,

00:49:09.070 --> 00:49:11.630
many things related to
heritability in general,

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:13.140
work in that way.

00:49:13.140 --> 00:49:15.360
And we know there's a
strong genetic component

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:16.193
to depression.

00:49:16.193 --> 00:49:17.026
How do we know?

00:49:17.026 --> 00:49:21.100
Well, in what are called
concordant monozygotic twins.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:23.630
So these will be identical twins.

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:26.810
And they can either be
in one biological sack

00:49:26.810 --> 00:49:30.100
or two biological sacks while in utero,

00:49:30.100 --> 00:49:32.840
what's called monochorionic
or dichorionic.

00:49:32.840 --> 00:49:35.650
Well, typically it's monochorionic.

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:39.590
And identical twins, for
which one of those twins

00:49:39.590 --> 00:49:41.070
goes on to have major depression,

00:49:41.070 --> 00:49:43.470
there's a 50% probability
that the other one

00:49:43.470 --> 00:49:44.630
will have major depression.

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:48.180
So it's not 100%, it's not 100% inherited,

00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:50.910
it's not 100% generic, as you might say,

00:49:50.910 --> 00:49:55.700
but there's a much higher
predisposition for depression.

00:49:55.700 --> 00:49:59.550
Whereas in fraternal
twins, that number drops,

00:49:59.550 --> 00:50:02.660
and in siblings, that
number drops to about 25%,

00:50:02.660 --> 00:50:05.410
and in half siblings, it's about 10%.

00:50:05.410 --> 00:50:07.150
The numbers vary from study to study,

00:50:07.150 --> 00:50:09.260
but basically the more
closely related you are

00:50:09.260 --> 00:50:13.080
to somebody who has major
depression, the more likely it is

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:14.550
that you will also get major depression.

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:17.140
And therefore, if you haven't
gotten major depression,

00:50:17.140 --> 00:50:20.640
the more likely it is
that you should take steps

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:22.690
to learn to mitigate stress

00:50:22.690 --> 00:50:24.170
because stress is the major factor

00:50:24.170 --> 00:50:27.360
that can trigger one of
these depressive episodes.

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:32.360
So we've covered a lot
related to the stress

00:50:32.610 --> 00:50:35.880
and the hormones and the
neurochemistry of depression.

00:50:35.880 --> 00:50:38.180
In fact, I think this is probably
the deepest I've ever gone

00:50:38.180 --> 00:50:40.990
into the biology of any
topic on this podcast

00:50:40.990 --> 00:50:43.730
before getting to any specific tools.

00:50:43.730 --> 00:50:45.670
I mentioned that learning
how to mitigate stress

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:46.503
and deal with stress,

00:50:46.503 --> 00:50:49.250
learning how to measure and
adjust your thyroid hormone,

00:50:49.250 --> 00:50:50.500
those might be useful.

00:50:50.500 --> 00:50:53.830
But next I'd like to turn
to some very specific tools

00:50:53.830 --> 00:50:57.150
that people who both have depression

00:50:57.150 --> 00:50:58.610
or who are prone to depression,

00:50:58.610 --> 00:51:00.070
as well as people who
don't have depression

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:02.580
and simply want to maintain a good mood,

00:51:02.580 --> 00:51:04.360
who want to maintain a positive affect

00:51:04.360 --> 00:51:05.930
and pursuit of things in life,

00:51:05.930 --> 00:51:07.370
what are the things that you can do?

00:51:07.370 --> 00:51:09.007
It turns out there are
things that you can do

00:51:09.007 --> 00:51:11.930
and all of the biology that underlies

00:51:11.930 --> 00:51:14.210
the utility of those things.

00:51:14.210 --> 00:51:16.460
Meaning the reasons those things work

00:51:16.460 --> 00:51:19.100
will now make sense to you
because they adjust things

00:51:19.100 --> 00:51:20.670
like serotonin and dopamine,

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:23.270
and they adjust them through
very specific pathways.

00:51:24.220 --> 00:51:26.900
I know for many people
learning about mechanism

00:51:26.900 --> 00:51:27.810
is kind of grueling.

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:29.880
I realized this podcast
isn't necessarily one

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:32.330
that you can listen to passively
while doing other things.

00:51:32.330 --> 00:51:34.800
Although I would hope
that you could do that

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:37.270
and still enjoy it and
extract the information.

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:38.210
Why mechanism?

00:51:38.210 --> 00:51:39.980
Mechanism is so key

00:51:39.980 --> 00:51:42.950
because mechanism is a
little bit like understanding

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:44.600
some of the chemistry of cooking.

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:48.870
If you read a recipe and
you can follow a recipe,

00:51:48.870 --> 00:51:52.480
you often hear people say,
oh, I can follow a recipe.

00:51:52.480 --> 00:51:55.470
That means that if you have
every ingredient in that recipe,

00:51:55.470 --> 00:51:56.303
you're good.

00:51:56.303 --> 00:51:59.750
You likely can make that
dish. You can make that meal.

00:51:59.750 --> 00:52:02.360
However, if you understand a
little bit of the chemistry

00:52:02.360 --> 00:52:06.860
of why salt has to be
added third and not first,

00:52:06.860 --> 00:52:09.850
or why the heat has to be
adjusted at a particular time,

00:52:09.850 --> 00:52:12.180
well then not only can
you follow a recipe,

00:52:12.180 --> 00:52:13.710
but that also gives you flexibility

00:52:13.710 --> 00:52:15.600
for when salt isn't available,

00:52:15.600 --> 00:52:18.400
or when you want to adjust
the flavor of the dish,

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:20.500
or when you want to try a new dish,

00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:21.690
or you want to get experimental.

00:52:21.690 --> 00:52:23.140
So when you understand mechanism,

00:52:23.140 --> 00:52:25.830
it puts you in a tremendous place of power

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:27.540
to work with your system.

00:52:27.540 --> 00:52:28.910
So it's not just plug and chug,

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:31.710
like take 12 milligrams of this,

00:52:31.710 --> 00:52:33.310
you either feel better or you don't.

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:37.100
You can really start to
understand how prescription drugs,

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:41.530
supplements, nutrition, behavioral tools,

00:52:41.530 --> 00:52:43.830
how those things weave
together to either work for you

00:52:43.830 --> 00:52:46.370
or not work for you and get you to paths

00:52:46.370 --> 00:52:49.220
of healthy mind and body.

00:52:49.220 --> 00:52:52.020
So let's think about
why any tool would work

00:52:52.020 --> 00:52:53.560
to relieve depression.

00:52:53.560 --> 00:52:54.940
We've talked about how some of the drugs

00:52:54.940 --> 00:52:57.300
that impact these different
chemical systems might work

00:52:57.300 --> 00:53:00.260
and why they create some of
the problems they create.

00:53:00.260 --> 00:53:02.940
Problems are mainly created
by the fact that they impact

00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:04.550
lots of systems in the brain and body.

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:06.880
So you take a drug to increase serotonin,

00:53:06.880 --> 00:53:10.270
but that serotonin is also
related, not just to mood,

00:53:10.270 --> 00:53:12.510
but to things related
to libido and appetite.

00:53:12.510 --> 00:53:15.063
And so you start disrupting
multiple systems.

00:53:16.310 --> 00:53:19.000
The same could be said for
behavioral tools, right?

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:22.220
That any behavioral tool
that adjusts the levels

00:53:22.220 --> 00:53:25.530
of a particular chemical ought to perhaps,

00:53:25.530 --> 00:53:27.310
provide some relief for
some of the symptoms

00:53:27.310 --> 00:53:28.750
of major depression.

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:31.620
Let's take an example that
I've talked about before

00:53:31.620 --> 00:53:32.690
on the podcast, which is,

00:53:32.690 --> 00:53:35.670
if you get into a very cold
shower, you take an ice bath,

00:53:35.670 --> 00:53:38.120
you will release
norepinephrine and epinephrine

00:53:38.120 --> 00:53:38.953
in your brain and body.

00:53:38.953 --> 00:53:40.950
There's no question about that.

00:53:40.950 --> 00:53:43.070
I don't think anyone
can really escape that.

00:53:43.070 --> 00:53:46.720
It's a kind of a universal
response to being in cold water.

00:53:46.720 --> 00:53:49.730
Well, if some aspects of depression

00:53:49.730 --> 00:53:52.370
are related to low
levels of norepinephrine,

00:53:52.370 --> 00:53:55.700
will taking cold showers
relieve your depression?

00:53:55.700 --> 00:53:58.010
Perhaps it might even
relieve certain aspects

00:53:58.010 --> 00:53:58.960
of that depression.

00:53:58.960 --> 00:54:01.860
Is it a cure? Well, that's going
to depend on the individual.

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:04.020
Will exercise help?

00:54:04.020 --> 00:54:05.720
Well, if you go out for a run,

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:07.950
you're going to increase
the amount of norepinephrine

00:54:07.950 --> 00:54:09.110
in your body.

00:54:09.110 --> 00:54:12.410
If you enjoy that run, it's
likely that you'll increase

00:54:12.410 --> 00:54:15.160
the levels of dopamine
and probably serotonin

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:16.880
in your brain and body as well.

00:54:16.880 --> 00:54:18.030
Will that cure your depression?

00:54:18.030 --> 00:54:20.220
Well, there are a lot of studies exploring

00:54:20.220 --> 00:54:22.060
how exercise can impact depression.

00:54:22.060 --> 00:54:24.980
And indeed, regular
exercise is known to be

00:54:24.980 --> 00:54:28.033
a protective behavior against depression,

00:54:29.350 --> 00:54:30.510
but it also can help relieve

00:54:30.510 --> 00:54:32.520
some of the symptoms of depression.

00:54:32.520 --> 00:54:35.450
So you may ask yourself, why
would you need drugs at all?

00:54:35.450 --> 00:54:37.550
Why would there be prescription drugs

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:39.610
or the need for
supplementation or other things

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:41.650
to alleviate the symptoms of depression?

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:44.930
Ah, well, that's the diabolical
nature of depression,

00:54:44.930 --> 00:54:49.910
which is if people are far
enough along in this thing,

00:54:49.910 --> 00:54:52.530
this sometimes called disease,
sometimes called disorder,

00:54:52.530 --> 00:54:57.530
but major depression, oftentimes
they can't get the energy

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:00.850
to even get up and take
a bath or a shower.

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:03.140
They have no motivation to do it,

00:55:03.140 --> 00:55:05.200
they have no desire to go for a run.

00:55:05.200 --> 00:55:06.847
So you say, "Come on, let's
go, you'll feel better.

00:55:06.847 --> 00:55:08.887
"I know you feel better, it
generates all these chemicals

00:55:08.887 --> 00:55:11.967
"I heard on the whatever
podcast, Huberman Lab podcast,

00:55:11.967 --> 00:55:14.197
"or another podcast
that getting into action

00:55:14.197 --> 00:55:15.420
"does all these things."

00:55:15.420 --> 00:55:16.690
And they just don't want to do it.

00:55:16.690 --> 00:55:20.210
And to you, a person who's
not experiencing depression,

00:55:20.210 --> 00:55:22.070
that perhaps could just seem
like the most frustrating

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:23.700
and confusing thing in the world.

00:55:23.700 --> 00:55:25.170
But it's very important to highlight

00:55:25.170 --> 00:55:26.900
the fact that these circuits

00:55:26.900 --> 00:55:29.090
that are accessible to some of us,

00:55:29.090 --> 00:55:31.720
the circuits for happiness,
for pursuit of pleasure,

00:55:31.720 --> 00:55:36.410
for exercise, for
getting in a cold shower,

00:55:36.410 --> 00:55:37.620
if that's your thing,

00:55:37.620 --> 00:55:40.990
that those circuits are
present in all people,

00:55:40.990 --> 00:55:42.570
but for certain people

00:55:42.570 --> 00:55:44.486
that are experiencing major depression

00:55:44.486 --> 00:55:47.010
and are really in the
depths of their depression,

00:55:47.010 --> 00:55:50.650
they can't really access
those circuits in the same way

00:55:50.650 --> 00:55:54.210
that people who are not
suffering from depression can.

00:55:54.210 --> 00:55:55.230
So I hope that makes it clear.

00:55:55.230 --> 00:55:57.400
It's not offering any excuses for them.

00:55:57.400 --> 00:56:00.470
And indeed, I think those
behaviors would help

00:56:00.470 --> 00:56:04.420
jolt them out of some of the
symptomology of depression,

00:56:04.420 --> 00:56:07.250
but they're just not
accessible to everybody.

00:56:07.250 --> 00:56:10.750
So let's talk about the
things that people can do

00:56:10.750 --> 00:56:12.220
to deal with depression.

00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:15.100
And again, anytime you add a behavior

00:56:15.100 --> 00:56:16.990
or a tool or a supplement,

00:56:16.990 --> 00:56:19.960
or subtract a behavior, tool,
supplement, drug, et cetera,

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:21.720
you absolutely should
talk to your physician,

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:23.140
especially if you're somebody

00:56:23.140 --> 00:56:25.220
that's dealing with major depression.

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:27.890
I want to focus on the stress system.

00:56:27.890 --> 00:56:29.860
And I'm not just going to tell you

00:56:29.860 --> 00:56:31.210
to get sunlight in your eyes

00:56:31.210 --> 00:56:32.440
and to get a good night's sleep,

00:56:32.440 --> 00:56:33.980
although I think everybody should do that

