It is available in its
full form at zero cost

01:37:02.120 --> 01:37:02.953
if you want to read it.

01:37:02.953 --> 01:37:03.840
It's got a lot of detail.

01:37:03.840 --> 01:37:05.410
So I'm just going to
summarize a few things,

01:37:05.410 --> 01:37:09.510
but basically what they did
was they screened for patients

01:37:09.510 --> 01:37:10.430
to come into the clinic.

01:37:10.430 --> 01:37:11.460
These were people that suffered

01:37:11.460 --> 01:37:13.870
from major depressive disorder,

01:37:13.870 --> 01:37:18.870
and administered either one
or two rounds of psilocybin.

01:37:20.300 --> 01:37:22.660
They used particular dosages
that are listed in the study.

01:37:22.660 --> 01:37:24.020
So you can look it up if
you're really interested

01:37:24.020 --> 01:37:25.710
in that level of detail.

01:37:25.710 --> 01:37:29.290
Typically it was 20 milligrams
per kilogram of body weight.

01:37:29.290 --> 01:37:30.830
So it depends on body weight.

01:37:30.830 --> 01:37:35.390
Or 30 milligrams of
psilocybin per 70 kilograms

01:37:35.390 --> 01:37:36.960
of body weight.

01:37:36.960 --> 01:37:38.140
They were given in capsule form.

01:37:38.140 --> 01:37:39.640
So people weren't eating the mushrooms.

01:37:39.640 --> 01:37:42.440
This is obviously a very controlled study

01:37:42.440 --> 01:37:46.230
and they wanted to control
the dosages appropriately.

01:37:46.230 --> 01:37:48.650
They were randomized to begin
the treatment immediately

01:37:48.650 --> 01:37:50.800
or after an eight week delay.

01:37:50.800 --> 01:37:52.480
They had all the
appropriate control groups

01:37:52.480 --> 01:37:54.010
that one would like to see.

01:37:54.010 --> 01:37:56.430
What's really striking this study

01:37:56.430 --> 01:38:00.760
is that there was a very
significant improvement

01:38:00.760 --> 01:38:04.370
in mood and affect and relief
from depressive symptoms

01:38:04.370 --> 01:38:09.210
in anywhere from 50 to 70% of the people

01:38:09.210 --> 01:38:12.480
that were subjects in
the study who received

01:38:13.990 --> 01:38:16.170
the psilocybin treatment.

01:38:16.170 --> 01:38:19.070
And whether or not it was 50
or whether or not it was 71%,

01:38:20.100 --> 01:38:23.110
varied according to how
long after the study

01:38:23.110 --> 01:38:25.420
they maintain these
antidepressive effects,

01:38:25.420 --> 01:38:27.700
whether or not they stayed in
remission from the depression,

01:38:27.700 --> 01:38:30.847
but these are really enormous
insignificant effects,

01:38:30.847 --> 01:38:35.670
and very exciting and are
pointing in the direction

01:38:35.670 --> 01:38:39.670
of psilocybin very soon,
becoming a treatment

01:38:39.670 --> 01:38:43.840
for various forms of depression,
including major depression.

01:38:43.840 --> 01:38:47.080
Now, of course, this is
limited to the laboratory

01:38:47.080 --> 01:38:48.210
at present.

01:38:48.210 --> 01:38:50.180
There are a number of
elements of these studies

01:38:50.180 --> 01:38:52.020
that are important to take
into consideration too,

01:38:52.020 --> 01:38:55.380
which is that there are
highly trained guides,

01:38:55.380 --> 01:38:58.650
meaning people to direct
people through the experience.

01:38:58.650 --> 01:39:00.710
As Matthew Johnson has told me,

01:39:00.710 --> 01:39:03.640
there is the occurrence from time to time

01:39:03.640 --> 01:39:05.410
of people having so-called bad trips

01:39:05.410 --> 01:39:08.000
of having anxiety attacks
during the hallucinations

01:39:08.000 --> 01:39:08.833
and all that.

01:39:08.833 --> 01:39:10.980
And they have ways to mitigate
that and deal with that

01:39:10.980 --> 01:39:12.810
because the guides are trained.

01:39:12.810 --> 01:39:16.730
They have all the sorts of
medical monitoring devices

01:39:16.730 --> 01:39:18.300
for heart rate and temperature and things

01:39:18.300 --> 01:39:22.010
that one would like to
see for a study like this,

01:39:22.010 --> 01:39:24.330
because these are very powerful compounds.

01:39:24.330 --> 01:39:26.830
I don't want to give away any
elements of the discussion

01:39:26.830 --> 01:39:28.310
with Matthew Johnson,

01:39:28.310 --> 01:39:30.470
because it will be
released in podcast form

01:39:30.470 --> 01:39:33.800
reasonably soon here,
the Huberman Lab podcast.

01:39:33.800 --> 01:39:35.580
But one of the things that came up

01:39:35.580 --> 01:39:37.180
and is a fundamental question that I had,

01:39:37.180 --> 01:39:38.880
that I think probably
many of you are asking,

01:39:38.880 --> 01:39:43.820
is does the experience that
one has on these compounds

01:39:43.820 --> 01:39:46.500
make a difference for whether
or not somebody gains relief

01:39:46.500 --> 01:39:50.800
from depression, from these
psilocybin journeys or not?

01:39:50.800 --> 01:39:52.820
In other words, does it
matter what they talk about?

01:39:52.820 --> 01:39:53.950
Does it matter what they think about?

01:39:53.950 --> 01:39:56.020
Does it matter if they have
a good trip or a bad trip?

01:39:56.020 --> 01:39:58.740
And I don't want to hold
you in too much suspense,

01:39:58.740 --> 01:40:00.990
I'll let Matthew provide
the more thorough answer.

01:40:00.990 --> 01:40:02.650
But what's really interesting

01:40:02.650 --> 01:40:07.650
is there are some common themes
to psilocybin administration

01:40:08.330 --> 01:40:11.460
and experience that lead to
relief from depressive symptoms,

01:40:11.460 --> 01:40:16.460
but they are subjectively very varied,

01:40:17.500 --> 01:40:20.520
meaning that whether or not people feel

01:40:20.520 --> 01:40:22.570
they had a good experience
or a bad experience,

01:40:22.570 --> 01:40:24.650
whether or not people
thought about their parents

01:40:24.650 --> 01:40:27.470
or thought about the color of the ceiling,

01:40:27.470 --> 01:40:30.170
doesn't seem to have too much of an impact

01:40:30.170 --> 01:40:32.840
on whether or not they receive relief

01:40:32.840 --> 01:40:36.323
during these studies in
these clinical studies.

01:40:37.270 --> 01:40:38.900
It seems like different people can have

01:40:38.900 --> 01:40:42.810
lots of different experiences
and still receive benefit.

01:40:42.810 --> 01:40:45.470
And that points to something deeper.

01:40:45.470 --> 01:40:48.200
It points to the fact that these drugs,

01:40:48.200 --> 01:40:49.830
which is really what they are,

01:40:49.830 --> 01:40:53.830
are rewiring neural
circuitry in a common way

01:40:53.830 --> 01:40:57.030
despite a diversity of
experience while on the drug.

01:40:57.030 --> 01:40:58.750
And that itself is really interesting.

01:40:58.750 --> 01:41:01.150
And it takes us back to a
place that we've been before

01:41:01.150 --> 01:41:04.110
in this discussion, which
is layer five of the cortex.

01:41:04.110 --> 01:41:06.560
This area that ketamine
seems to impact as well

01:41:06.560 --> 01:41:08.223
by generating rhythms of the,

01:41:08.223 --> 01:41:10.210
I mentioned one to three Hertz activity

01:41:10.210 --> 01:41:13.290
in layer five of certain
areas of the cortex.

01:41:13.290 --> 01:41:17.520
Well, the 5HT1A receptor
is known to be enriched

01:41:17.520 --> 01:41:19.850
in layer five of the cortex,

01:41:19.850 --> 01:41:23.570
and layer five of the cortex
is a very interesting area

01:41:23.570 --> 01:41:25.130
because it's an area in which

01:41:25.130 --> 01:41:27.340
there's a lot of lateral connectivity.

01:41:27.340 --> 01:41:30.680
So connections between
different brain areas laterally,

01:41:30.680 --> 01:41:34.600
generally is what allows us
to merge different senses.

01:41:34.600 --> 01:41:37.050
So for instance, when we
hear a sound off to our right

01:41:37.050 --> 01:41:39.240
over here, we turn to our right.

01:41:39.240 --> 01:41:41.050
There's a very hardwired response.

01:41:41.050 --> 01:41:42.720
And typically we hear
something off to our right,

01:41:42.720 --> 01:41:44.190
we don't look to our left.

01:41:44.190 --> 01:41:46.750
That's how hardwired some
of these circuits are.

01:41:46.750 --> 01:41:49.370
What appears to be happening
is that the activation

01:41:49.370 --> 01:41:53.630
of the serotonin system and
5HT1A receptor in layer five

01:41:53.630 --> 01:41:57.490
is offering up or providing an experience

01:41:57.490 --> 01:42:01.300
whereby the lateral
connections are able to engage

01:42:01.300 --> 01:42:03.880
much more broadly than
they would normally.

01:42:03.880 --> 01:42:07.120
Now that also could be a bad thing.

01:42:07.120 --> 01:42:10.530
And I asked Matt about this,
that sounds kind of spooky.

01:42:10.530 --> 01:42:12.660
I don't know that when I hear
something off to my right,

01:42:12.660 --> 01:42:13.950
that I want to look off to my left.

01:42:13.950 --> 01:42:15.490
That could be highly maladaptive,

01:42:15.490 --> 01:42:18.500
especially if it's a car
coming at me from my right.

01:42:18.500 --> 01:42:20.030
That doesn't seem to be what's happening.

01:42:20.030 --> 01:42:24.080
It's not really rewiring these
deeply reflexive circuits.

01:42:24.080 --> 01:42:27.720
It's somehow rewiring
associations between events,

01:42:27.720 --> 01:42:30.280
emotional events, past
events, current events,

01:42:30.280 --> 01:42:33.140
and future events in
ways that allow people

01:42:33.140 --> 01:42:35.750
to get some sort of relief or distance

01:42:35.750 --> 01:42:39.180
from these narratives,
these depressive stories

01:42:39.180 --> 01:42:41.500
about their past and
present and allow them

01:42:41.500 --> 01:42:44.373
to see new opportunity and
optimism in the future.

01:42:44.373 --> 01:42:47.020
It's really a fascinating thing

01:42:47.020 --> 01:42:48.440
if you really think about it,

01:42:48.440 --> 01:42:50.510
because I would have thought

01:42:50.510 --> 01:42:53.910
that simply by ramping up
laterality of connections,

01:42:53.910 --> 01:42:56.100
meaning that cross associations,

01:42:56.100 --> 01:42:59.680
that things could either
be rewired randomly

01:42:59.680 --> 01:43:01.300
in ways that don't serve us,

01:43:01.300 --> 01:43:04.900
or would perhaps just
cause no effect at all.

01:43:04.900 --> 01:43:06.520
So it's either going to be bad or neutral,

01:43:06.520 --> 01:43:08.730
but that's not really the
way things are turning out.

01:43:08.730 --> 01:43:10.640
Again, these are highly
controlled studies.

01:43:10.640 --> 01:43:13.210
I do want to emphasize
that ketamine, psilocybin,

01:43:13.210 --> 01:43:14.780
these things are still illegal.

01:43:14.780 --> 01:43:16.500
Most all places.

01:43:16.500 --> 01:43:19.190
There are some regions and
cities in the United States

01:43:19.190 --> 01:43:21.470
where they are locally decriminalized,

01:43:21.470 --> 01:43:22.600
but they are not legal.

01:43:22.600 --> 01:43:23.560
They're still illegal.

01:43:23.560 --> 01:43:26.550
So what we're referring to here
are indeed clinical studies

01:43:26.550 --> 01:43:29.810
in which people are taking them legally.

01:43:29.810 --> 01:43:32.940
I think it's very likely
we will see a shift

01:43:32.940 --> 01:43:35.420
in the legislature around psychedelics,

01:43:35.420 --> 01:43:39.720
and in particular, psilocybin
in the not too distant future.

01:43:39.720 --> 01:43:43.190
And I think that for
now, what we should know

01:43:43.190 --> 01:43:47.113
is what Matt told me and what
you'll hear far more about,

01:43:48.190 --> 01:43:52.690
which is that psilocybin.
this one where in most cases,

01:43:52.690 --> 01:43:55.970
two dose treatments done in
a highly clinical setting,

01:43:55.970 --> 01:43:58.560
controlled setting with patients

01:43:58.560 --> 01:44:01.610
that are carefully
selected, can in many cases,

01:44:01.610 --> 01:44:05.310
the majority of people
receive and maintain relief

01:44:05.310 --> 01:44:07.160
from their depressive symptoms,

01:44:07.160 --> 01:44:11.540
simply through the experience
of this psychedelic journey.

01:44:11.540 --> 01:44:13.603
I did ask them about micro dosing.

01:44:14.960 --> 01:44:17.008
I made it sound as if I'd
never heard about it before.

01:44:17.008 --> 01:44:18.940
Microdosing, not micro dosing.

01:44:18.940 --> 01:44:22.700
Microdosing, and his
answer was interesting.

01:44:22.700 --> 01:44:25.520
His answer was that
the microdosing effects

01:44:25.520 --> 01:44:28.603
don't seem to be nearly as
impactful as some of these,

01:44:29.850 --> 01:44:31.350
well, let's just call them what they are.

01:44:31.350 --> 01:44:34.530
These kind of high amplitude sessions

01:44:34.530 --> 01:44:37.860
that there are just one or two,

01:44:37.860 --> 01:44:40.780
there are some studies ongoing
where there's more than two,

01:44:40.780 --> 01:44:43.180
but that the microdosing
doesn't seem to compare

01:44:43.180 --> 01:44:47.660
to these macrodosing, I
mentioned the dosages before,

01:44:47.660 --> 01:44:49.670
this 20 milligrams per 70 kilograms

01:44:49.670 --> 01:44:53.159
or 30 milligrams per 70 kilograms dosages

01:44:53.159 --> 01:44:56.010
given several weeks apart.

01:44:56.010 --> 01:44:58.270
So you'll hear more about microdosing

01:44:58.270 --> 01:45:00.480
and other psychedelics and their impact

01:45:00.480 --> 01:45:04.230
on depressive states and major depression

01:45:04.230 --> 01:45:05.690
in the episode with Matt.

01:45:05.690 --> 01:45:08.270
But for the time being, it
really seems as if, again,

01:45:08.270 --> 01:45:09.620
we're looking at neuroplasticity,

01:45:09.620 --> 01:45:11.080
we're coming back to layer five,

01:45:11.080 --> 01:45:13.100
just like with ketamine and PCP.

01:45:13.100 --> 01:45:14.370
We're hearing about layer five,

01:45:14.370 --> 01:45:15.980
we're hearing about rewiring of circuitry,

01:45:15.980 --> 01:45:18.610
we're hearing about a
dissociation or a distancing

01:45:18.610 --> 01:45:23.300
of oneself from these
negative moods and affects

01:45:23.300 --> 01:45:25.880
and narratives, but
there's a key distinction

01:45:26.760 --> 01:45:30.170
between the ketamine work
and the psilocybin work,

01:45:30.170 --> 01:45:31.550
which is that in the ketamine work,

01:45:31.550 --> 01:45:34.610
it really is about
dissociating from experience

01:45:34.610 --> 01:45:36.850
during the session with the psychiatrist,

01:45:36.850 --> 01:45:38.790
whereas during the psilocybin journey,

01:45:38.790 --> 01:45:41.770
it's really about immersing
oneself in the experience

01:45:41.770 --> 01:45:43.890
and being fully present
to that experience.

01:45:43.890 --> 01:45:45.750
That does seem to be
an important component

01:45:45.750 --> 01:45:47.490
and what the difference is there

01:45:47.490 --> 01:45:50.600
and why they both seem
to provide some relief

01:45:50.600 --> 01:45:53.480
from major depression isn't clear.

01:45:53.480 --> 01:45:56.430
I think most likely it
takes us back to the fact

01:45:56.430 --> 01:45:59.290
that this thing we call major depression

01:45:59.290 --> 01:46:03.530
clearly involves serotonin,
dopamine, and norepinephrine.

01:46:03.530 --> 01:46:06.190
And in some individuals,
they may be more deficient

01:46:06.190 --> 01:46:08.650
in one or several of
those or all of those,

01:46:08.650 --> 01:46:09.780
whereas in other individuals,

01:46:09.780 --> 01:46:12.230
it might be a different
collection of chemicals.

01:46:12.230 --> 01:46:14.410
And of course there
are a tremendous number

01:46:14.410 --> 01:46:18.620
of other psychedelic compounds
that people are exploring

01:46:18.620 --> 01:46:21.270
for treatment of major depression.

01:46:21.270 --> 01:46:22.650
But really psilocybin is the one

01:46:22.650 --> 01:46:24.590
that we have the most data on.

01:46:24.590 --> 01:46:29.100
MDMA has mainly been explored
in the clinical realm

01:46:29.100 --> 01:46:30.300
for treatment of trauma.

01:46:30.300 --> 01:46:34.470
There are some trials ongoing
for treatment of depression,

01:46:34.470 --> 01:46:38.200
but the big breakthrough
seemed to be happening

01:46:38.200 --> 01:46:40.440
in the realm of trauma treatment,

01:46:40.440 --> 01:46:42.520
the so-called maps
group that's doing this,

01:46:42.520 --> 01:46:44.890
again, legally in a clinical setting.

01:46:44.890 --> 01:46:45.890
And there are other groups

01:46:45.890 --> 01:46:47.310
that are starting to do it as well.

01:46:47.310 --> 01:46:50.557
We are going to do an
entire podcast about MDMA

01:46:50.557 --> 01:46:52.240
and some related compounds.

01:46:52.240 --> 01:46:54.610
So I'll save that discussion for then.

01:46:54.610 --> 01:46:57.370
One of the most common
questions I get for this podcast

01:46:57.370 --> 01:47:00.760
is about different
diets, different regimes,

01:47:00.760 --> 01:47:03.377
different nutritional
plans, things like keto,

01:47:03.377 --> 01:47:08.040
ketogenic diet, or vegan
diets, or intermittent fasting,

01:47:08.040 --> 01:47:11.790
or the all meat diet, the
so-called lion diet, et cetera.

01:47:11.790 --> 01:47:14.410
There are actually really interesting data

01:47:14.410 --> 01:47:18.760
relating nutrition and diet
to major depressive disorder.

01:47:18.760 --> 01:47:21.690
And I think we just need to frame this

01:47:21.690 --> 01:47:23.600
by returning to something
that was said earlier,

01:47:23.600 --> 01:47:26.720
which is that the
ingestion of carbohydrates,

01:47:26.720 --> 01:47:29.680
in particular carbohydrates
and some meats like turkey,

01:47:29.680 --> 01:47:34.680
that are rich in tryptophan,
this precursor to serotonin,

01:47:34.680 --> 01:47:39.680
are in many ways the
self-medicating version

01:47:39.770 --> 01:47:41.750
of depression treatment.

01:47:41.750 --> 01:47:43.180
Now, to be clear, I'm not saying

01:47:43.180 --> 01:47:46.140
that people should use food
to medicate their depression.

01:47:46.140 --> 01:47:48.350
Many people do that reflexively however,

01:47:48.350 --> 01:47:50.270
they reach for carbohydrate rich foods

01:47:50.270 --> 01:47:53.790
to blunt their cortisol, because
that's indeed what it does.

01:47:53.790 --> 01:47:56.120
It blunts cortisol when you
ingest high carbohydrate foods,

01:47:56.120 --> 01:47:57.750
in particular starchy foods,

01:47:57.750 --> 01:48:00.840
and it does increase serotonin,

01:48:00.840 --> 01:48:04.810
in particular, if those
foods rather are rich

01:48:04.810 --> 01:48:06.940
in the amino acid tryptophan.

01:48:06.940 --> 01:48:10.360
Now ingesting food is wonderful
and important and great,

01:48:10.360 --> 01:48:12.420
but ingesting excessive
foods of any kinds,

01:48:12.420 --> 01:48:16.470
carbohydrate or otherwise
it's not healthy, of course.

01:48:16.470 --> 01:48:19.240
There have been some explorations

01:48:19.240 --> 01:48:22.050
of whether or not a vegan diet can improve

01:48:22.050 --> 01:48:23.150
symptoms of depression.

01:48:23.150 --> 01:48:25.500
Not a lot of data, not impressive data.

01:48:25.500 --> 01:48:27.750
There have been very
few controlled studies

01:48:27.750 --> 01:48:31.140
looking at the carnivore or all meat diet.

01:48:31.140 --> 01:48:32.740
On that, I think there are now some

01:48:32.740 --> 01:48:34.060
that are starting to spin up,

01:48:34.060 --> 01:48:35.580
meaning those studies
are starting to spin up.

01:48:35.580 --> 01:48:39.170
However, the ketogenic
diet has been explored

01:48:39.170 --> 01:48:44.000
for its ability to relieve
certain symptoms of depression,

01:48:45.130 --> 01:48:49.461
in particular to what's
called maintain euthymia.

01:48:49.461 --> 01:48:51.850
Euthymia is the kind
of state of equilibrium

01:48:51.850 --> 01:48:55.060
between a manic episode
and a depressive episode

01:48:55.060 --> 01:48:56.380
in a manic bipolar person.

01:48:56.380 --> 01:48:58.250
We'll return to this
more in a future episode,

01:48:58.250 --> 01:49:01.890
but it basically, maniacs
have highs and they have lows,

01:49:01.890 --> 01:49:04.360
bipolars, either cycle back
and forth really quickly.

01:49:04.360 --> 01:49:07.400
So rapid cycling bipolars
or slow, some people

01:49:07.400 --> 01:49:09.250
So really quickly can be day to day,

01:49:09.250 --> 01:49:11.160
other people it's month
to month or week to week,

01:49:11.160 --> 01:49:13.490
they're going highs and lows.

01:49:13.490 --> 01:49:16.090
And you hear about mania and
you hear about dysphoria,

01:49:16.090 --> 01:49:19.200
euthymia is that kind
of place in the middle

01:49:19.200 --> 01:49:22.890
where people feel neither
too high nor too low.

01:49:22.890 --> 01:49:25.210
And there are some interesting studies

01:49:25.210 --> 01:49:28.450
looking at the ketogenic
diet for maintaining euthymia

01:49:28.450 --> 01:49:29.740
in manic depressives,

01:49:29.740 --> 01:49:32.570
but also in people with
major depressive disorder.

01:49:32.570 --> 01:49:33.630
Why would this work?

01:49:33.630 --> 01:49:36.630
Well, we have to remember
that the ketogenic diet

01:49:36.630 --> 01:49:41.460
wasn't discovered so that
self appointed nutrition gurus

01:49:41.460 --> 01:49:44.410
could talk about it
online or so that people

01:49:44.410 --> 01:49:48.050
could make money selling
anything related to ketosis.

01:49:48.050 --> 01:49:49.970
And here I'm not disparaging
of the ketogenic diet.

01:49:49.970 --> 01:49:50.803
It's helped a lot of people.

01:49:50.803 --> 01:49:53.640
The ketogenic diet was actually shown

01:49:53.640 --> 01:49:58.640
to be medically relevant for
its use to treat epilepsy.

01:49:59.930 --> 01:50:02.840
It turns out that in epilepsy,

01:50:02.840 --> 01:50:05.330
or in particular pediatric epilepsy,

01:50:05.330 --> 01:50:09.620
that a ketogenic diet and
the shift of brain metabolism

01:50:09.620 --> 01:50:12.870
to predominantly one in which
ketones are being metabolized

01:50:12.870 --> 01:50:17.720
rather than more standard
glucose tight metabolism,

01:50:17.720 --> 01:50:20.820
can greatly reduce the
number of epileptic seizures

01:50:20.820 --> 01:50:22.780
that these children experience.

01:50:22.780 --> 01:50:24.357
It's not always the case,
but it's often the case.

01:50:24.357 --> 01:50:27.360
And so you talk to a
neurologist or a neurosurgeon

01:50:27.360 --> 01:50:31.350
who's specialized in epilepsy,

01:50:31.350 --> 01:50:34.087
in particular pediatric epilepsy,
and they'll tell you this,

01:50:34.087 --> 01:50:36.817
"Oh yeah, the ketogenic
diet, in many cases, not all,

01:50:36.817 --> 01:50:38.780
"can be very effective
for this treatment."

01:50:38.780 --> 01:50:40.000
How?

01:50:40.000 --> 01:50:43.640
How is it that a ketogenic
diet reduces seizures?

01:50:43.640 --> 01:50:46.420
Well, the way it reduces seizures

01:50:46.420 --> 01:50:49.980
is by increasing what's
called GABA transmission.

01:50:49.980 --> 01:50:54.300
GABA is a substance that is
naturally released in our brain.

01:50:54.300 --> 01:50:56.400
It's an inhibitory neurotransmitter,

01:50:56.400 --> 01:50:59.010
meaning that when it's
released into the synapse,

01:50:59.010 --> 01:51:01.760
it has the tendency to reduce the firing,

01:51:01.760 --> 01:51:04.760
to reduce the electrical
activity of the next neuron

01:51:04.760 --> 01:51:06.023
or sets of neurons.

01:51:06.970 --> 01:51:09.550
There are various compounds
that increase GABA,

01:51:09.550 --> 01:51:10.960
in particular, GABA in the forebrain.

01:51:10.960 --> 01:51:14.570
One common example would
be something like alcohol,

01:51:14.570 --> 01:51:16.960
drinking alcoholic drink or two

01:51:16.960 --> 01:51:18.990
will increase GABA transmission,

01:51:18.990 --> 01:51:23.010
ironically will lower
your social inhibitions

01:51:23.010 --> 01:51:26.010
by increasing your
neurochemical inhibition.

01:51:26.010 --> 01:51:30.060
It basically suppresses the
self-monitoring pathways.

01:51:30.060 --> 01:51:31.030
And if people drink enough,

01:51:31.030 --> 01:51:32.247
it will suppress all pathways

01:51:32.247 --> 01:51:34.880
and people will urinate
themselves and fall over.

01:51:34.880 --> 01:51:37.520
It will eventually inhibit
all sorts of pathways.

01:51:37.520 --> 01:51:41.270
So the GABA system has
a rich array of effects

01:51:41.270 --> 01:51:42.960
all over the brain and body.

01:51:42.960 --> 01:51:47.190
But alcohol tends to
activate the release of GABA.

01:51:47.190 --> 01:51:49.550
You might say, well then
why not just take alcohol

01:51:49.550 --> 01:51:50.383
to suppress seizures?

01:51:50.383 --> 01:51:51.530
Well, that be a terrible idea

01:51:51.530 --> 01:51:54.170
because there tends to
be a rebound excitability

01:51:54.170 --> 01:51:57.720
after alcohol stops having its effects

01:51:57.720 --> 01:51:58.920
on the GABA receptors.

01:51:58.920 --> 01:52:00.690
And so then there's an excitability

01:52:00.690 --> 01:52:03.160
for which an epilepsy would be terrible.

01:52:03.160 --> 01:52:07.150
The reason why the epileptic
diet is useful for epilepsy

01:52:07.150 --> 01:52:09.627
is that increases what
we call the tonic level,

01:52:09.627 --> 01:52:13.890
the sort of the ti, the
level of GABA in the brain,

01:52:13.890 --> 01:52:16.630
and that suppresses some
of the hyperexcitability,

01:52:16.630 --> 01:52:20.220
that is the characteristic
feature of epilepsy.

01:52:20.220 --> 01:52:21.940
And there are other drugs, for instance,

01:52:21.940 --> 01:52:26.620
the benzodiazepines and
things of the Xanax, variety,

01:52:26.620 --> 01:52:28.260
Valium, and so forth.

01:52:28.260 --> 01:52:30.130
Those increased GABA transmission.

01:52:30.130 --> 01:52:32.670
Those drugs also have a
lot of potential for abuse

01:52:32.670 --> 01:52:34.040
and addiction, et cetera,

01:52:34.040 --> 01:52:36.010
and they're problematic for other reasons.

01:52:36.010 --> 01:52:38.660
But the ketogenic diet,

01:52:38.660 --> 01:52:40.950
by way of increasing ketone metabolism

01:52:40.950 --> 01:52:44.610
or shifting brain's
metabolism over to ketones

01:52:44.610 --> 01:52:49.610
tends to modulate GABA such
that GABA is more active

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:54.040
and adjust the so-called
GABA glutamate balance.

01:52:54.040 --> 01:52:55.050
This is getting technical,

01:52:55.050 --> 01:52:58.100
but glutamate is an
excitatory neurotransmitter,

01:52:58.100 --> 01:52:59.770
GABA is inhibitory neurotransmitter,

01:52:59.770 --> 01:53:02.520
and their balance is
vital for neuroplasticity,

01:53:02.520 --> 01:53:05.770
for maintaining healthy levels
of activity in the brain,

01:53:05.770 --> 01:53:06.830
et cetera.

01:53:06.830 --> 01:53:10.160
And so there is decent evidence

01:53:10.160 --> 01:53:13.370
that people with major
depressive disorders,

01:53:13.370 --> 01:53:17.190
in particular, the people with
major depressive disorders

01:53:17.190 --> 01:53:20.790
